\title{Autonomous Research Needs Self-Evolving Trial-and-Error Harnesses, Not Paper Generators}

\author{Anonymous Authors}

\begin{document}

\maketitle

\begin{abstract}
As LLM-driven agents become more capable, autonomous research is becoming a concrete systems problem. Existing autoresearch frameworks focus on scaffolds, tools, and pipelines that move agents from idea to manuscript. We argue that this is necessary but not sufficient. Strong research also requires accumulated judgment: the compressed experience that human researchers build through repeated attempts, failures, surprising successes, critique, and reflection. Autonomous research agents therefore need an experience substrate, not only static model knowledge and tool access. We propose Scientific Trial-and-Error Harnesses. A harness lets agents interact repeatedly with real research environments under bounded controls, preserves positive and negative outcomes, summarizes lessons into long-term memory, and uses those lessons to change future behavior. We operationalize this design with two auditable conversion targets. \emph{Trial-to-behavior conversion} maps a trial signal at iteration $t$ to a future action at iteration $t+k$ across planning, validation, claim maturity, scheduling, critique, and writing scope. \emph{Trial-to-harness-behavior conversion} turns recurring process failures into prompt overlays, validation gates, telemetry requirements, scheduler policies, repair tasks, and protected constraints. We instantiate this agent-harness co-evolution in \sibyl{}, a file-backed autonomous research harness deployed across seven primary workspaces and six diagnostic ablations. The audited traces show 411 tracked experiment tasks, 66 iteration directories, and per-workspace evolution memory files that route process failures back into harness updates. In \texttt{dynamic-wd}, a \texttt{REFINE} decision becomes a 14-task plan, UDWDC-v2 repair, 9/9 passing stability tests, and scoped \texttt{ADVANCE}; in \texttt{dlm-acceleration}, unsupported statistics and metric failures become hard gates, full-scale replication prerequisites, and a reframed interference taxonomy.
\end{abstract}


\section{Introduction}

As LLMs and LLM-driven agents improve in reasoning, coding, tool use, and long-horizon execution, autonomous research is becoming a concrete systems problem. The question is no longer only how human researchers can use LLMs as assistants. It is whether an agent can conduct a full research cycle with limited human intervention: search the literature, form hypotheses, choose methods, run experiments, interpret results, revise claims, and draft a paper.

Recent systems already automate many parts of this loop. End-to-end AI scientist systems move from idea generation to draft papers \citep{lu2024aiscientist,yamada2025aiscientistv2}. Research assistant and co-scientist systems help formulate hypotheses, synthesize literature, and rank candidates \citep{schmidgall2025agentlaboratory,gottweis2025aicoscientist,ghareeb2025robin}. Metric-driven loops modify code to optimize a visible score \citep{karpathy2026autoresearch}. These systems show that agents can participate in large parts of scientific work. They leave open a deeper question: what would let an agent improve as a researcher over repeated research attempts?

The current design target is often a scaffold, tool interface, or research pipeline. These structures give agents roles, tools, execution environments, and writing stages so they can complete research tasks. We argue that they are necessary but insufficient. A pipeline can produce a finished-looking paper while failing to carry forward the experience that an earlier metric was broken, a pilot was underpowered, a baseline was invalid, or a reviewer objection should have blocked a claim. Completing research stages is not the same as becoming better at research. The missing capability is accumulated judgment.

Human researchers produce good ideas, results, and papers not only because they know facts or can use tools. Effective researchers develop inspiration, taste, suspicion, and domain understanding through many concrete encounters with a field. They learn from implementation details, failed pilots, surprising successes, benchmark quirks, related work, reviewer objections, lab notes, and repeated reflection. We call this \emph{research judgment}: the practical form of what researchers often describe as intuition, taste, or domain understanding. It is compressed experience that tells a researcher what is worth trying, which metrics are fragile, which baselines are suspicious, when a negative result is informative, and when a polished story is running ahead of the evidence~\citep{ericsson1996expert}.

Autonomous research agents need an analogous experience substrate. Static model knowledge and tool access can start a research loop, but they cannot replace repeated trials in a real research environment. An agent must be able to try alternative theories and methods, inspect datasets and benchmarks, absorb critique, and reflect after each project. Past attempts should then shape future priors: what to try, what to distrust, what to validate, what to abandon, and how strongly to state a claim. Without this conversion, each project begins like a new researcher with no lab history.

\textbf{Autonomous research needs a Scientific Trial-and-Error Harness, not a paper generator.} A finished-looking paper can hide immature evidence. A harness is not merely a pipeline that moves an agent from idea to manuscript. It is the external research environment that lets agents interact with real research tasks under bounded controls, fail without corrupting the evidence base, preserve positive and negative outcomes, summarize lessons into long-term memory, and use those lessons to guide future behavior. A paper then expresses an evidence state. It is not the primary unit of research capability.

The bridge in this paper is \emph{trial-to-behavior conversion}: accumulated trial history visibly changes future research behavior. This is the observable footprint of accumulated research judgment in an autonomous system. A system has learned from a failed pilot when later plans ask for stronger controls, experiment agents run validation first, critics check the same metric failure, supervisors downgrade claims, schedulers prefer cheap sanity checks, or writers narrow the narrative. We also introduce \emph{trial-to-harness-behavior conversion}: recurring failures change the harness itself through new checks, prompt overlays, scheduler policies, telemetry requirements, repair tasks, or protected constraints. Together these two conversions define \emph{agent-harness co-evolution}: the agent accumulates domain judgment, while the harness learns how to make future research loops safer, cheaper, and more informative. Figure~\ref{fig:hook} gives the framing.

This position came from building \sibyl{}, a file-backed autonomous research harness, and inspecting traces from seven primary AI/ML research workspaces plus six diagnostic ablations. The harness functions below were not invented top-down. Each was a response to failures encountered while running computational autonomous research: missing figures across rounds, stale artifacts, underpowered experiments, broken proxy metrics, unsupported claims, GPU telemetry gaps, and synchronization failures between planning, evidence, and writing artifacts. In \sibyl{}, these traces become design pressure. Weak claims are sent back to validation, negative results influence future planning, recurring artifact failures become harness-level checks, and system weaknesses become repair targets.

