We make four contributions:
\begin{enumerate}
  \item \textbf{A judgment-centered framing for autonomous research.} We argue that autonomous research systems should be designed to accumulate \emph{research judgment}: the experience-backed ability to choose directions, distrust weak signals, interpret negative results, and calibrate claims across repeated research attempts.
  \item \textbf{Two auditable conversion definitions.} We introduce \emph{trial-to-behavior conversion} and \emph{trial-to-harness-behavior conversion} as concrete targets for asking whether trial history changes future research behavior and future harness behavior.
  \item \textbf{Scientific Trial-and-Error Harnesses.} We define the bounded, memory-bearing research environment that can produce these conversions by organizing trials, controlling evidence maturity, routing memory, separating perspectives, managing resources, preserving traces, and evolving the harness itself.
  \item \textbf{A concrete instantiation in \sibyl{}.} We instantiate this design in a file-backed autonomous research harness and audit it through seven primary AI/ML workspaces, six diagnostic ablations, and system-evolution records that expose how research traces become behavior updates and harness repairs.
\end{enumerate}

\section{Related work}

Autonomous research draws on several lines of work that make parts of the research process executable. End-to-end AI scientist systems show that LLM agents can generate ideas, run experiments, interpret results, and draft manuscripts \citep{lu2024aiscientist,yamada2025aiscientistv2}. Research assistant and co-scientist systems emphasize hypothesis generation, literature synthesis, human collaboration, and candidate prioritization \citep{schmidgall2025agentlaboratory,gottweis2025aicoscientist,ghareeb2025robin}. These systems establish that agents can participate in large portions of the scientific workflow.

Metric-driven autoresearch and verifier-rich systems demonstrate the value of repeated autonomous trials when feedback is clear. Autoresearch loops can search over code or methods against a visible objective \citep{karpathy2026autoresearch,analemma2026fars}, while AlphaEvolve-style systems exploit strong automatic evaluators in algorithmic spaces \citep{novikov2025alphaevolve}. PaperBench evaluates whether agents can reproduce existing AI research \citep{starace2025paperbench}. These settings clarify what becomes possible when a system can try, measure, and revise.

Long-running agent engineering contributes the infrastructure needed to keep such processes reliable: harnesses, tools, tracing, and guardrails \citep{anthropic2025harnesses,anthropic2025tools,openai2026tracing,openai2026guardrails}. Memory, reflection, provenance, and reproducibility work provide complementary ingredients for learning from previous attempts and grounding claims in artifacts \citep{shinn2023reflexion,packer2023memgpt,lebo2013provo,gundersen2018reproducibility,ioannidis2005why}. Reflection systems show that verbal lessons from failed trials can improve later agent behavior, and memory systems show how agents can structure information across long interactions. Our question is more specific: whether a research trial changes the role that must act on it, the maturity boundary that controls the claim, and the harness path that allowed the failure. Trial-to-behavior conversion is not only remembering a lesson in context. It requires an auditable route from trial signal to later plan, validation, claim scope, resource policy, or harness repair.

\section{Where autonomous research loses experience}

Autonomous research systems already make many research actions executable: agents can propose hypotheses, search literature, run code, optimize metrics, use tools, write drafts, preserve context, and expose traces. The core failure is subtler. A system can perform all of these actions and still lose the experience that should have been produced by them. The issue is not whether a weak claim, failed metric, negative result, reviewer objection, or process failure was observed. The issue is whether it changed what the system did next.

We call the missing object an \emph{update path}: the route by which a trial signal becomes a later constraint on planning, validation, claim scope, resource allocation, critique, writing, or harness behavior. Without update paths, autonomous research becomes a high-throughput activity generator. A paper becomes smoother while the evidence remains weak. A metric improves while the objective drifts away from the scientific question. A reflection says the right lesson while the next role ignores it. A long-running harness records the same missing artifact, stale table, or telemetry gap across projects without making the failure harder to repeat.

The common pressures are therefore not isolated bugs; they are places where scientific experience leaks out of the loop. Paper-as-endpoint systems lose the boundary between prose completion and evidence maturity. Cheap pilot loops lose the difference between a direction worth exploring and a claim worth publishing. Metric-driven loops lose the ability to question the metric itself. Long-context systems can remember a lesson textually while failing to route it to the planner, critic, scheduler, or writer who must act on it. Many-trial systems can increase experiment volume while failing to improve stopping rules, ordering, or sanity checks. Long-running harnesses can accumulate logs while failing to repair the process path that allowed repeated artifact or synchronization failures.

These pressures are visible in the raw workspaces. In \texttt{sae-absorption-kimi}, paper-facing quality reached 8/10 exactly when verification exposed byte-identical Matryoshka and MultiScale replicates, a 1024-versus-16,384 feature-count mismatch, missing L0 control, negative explained variance, and 81.6\% dead TopK latents. In \texttt{augmentation-order}, a CIFAR-10/ResNet18 pilot produced a 2.68 percentage-point spread and a \texttt{GO} signal, but reflection scored the project 4.0/10 and blocked full-scale claims because Tier-1 experiments remained unrun. In \texttt{dlm-acceleration}, fluent speedup claims contained fabricated Wilcoxon values, alpha and accept-rate mismatches, and a functional M1 no-op. In \texttt{dynamic-wd}, a \texttt{REFINE} decision did not become prose; it became UDWDC-v2 repair, budget assertions, 9/9 stability tests, and scoped \texttt{ADVANCE}. The diagnosis is therefore not abstract. The system must convert such signals into later behavior, or it has not learned from its own research.

Table~\ref{tab:failuremodes} restates these pressures as missing update paths. This framing is constructive: each failure mode points to a concrete system requirement. If pilot signals overclaim, the system needs maturity gates. If bad metrics recur, the system needs measurement critique and objective redesign. If lessons stay inert, it needs routed memory. If process failures recur, it needs harness evolution. Section~\ref{sec:harness} turns these requirements into the Scientific Trial-and-Error Harness framework.

