\section{Scientific Trial-and-Error as Agent-Harness Co-Evolution}
\label{sec:harness}

The diagnosis above changes the unit of analysis. The central unit of autonomous research is not the paper, the prompt, or the agent role. It is the \emph{trial}: a bounded encounter with a real research environment that produces a signal about a hypothesis, method, measurement, baseline, validation check, resource policy, or process. A trial is valuable when the signal changes future behavior. A failed trial can be especially valuable because it rules out a tempting story, exposes a fragile metric, or reveals a weakness in the surrounding research environment.

This is the operational version of research judgment. Human researchers acquire taste through repeated encounters with what worked, what failed, what fooled them, and what objections changed their standards. Autonomous systems need an analogous experience substrate. Static model knowledge can start a project, and tools can execute actions, but repeated trials are what let the agent form priors over what is promising, fragile, suspicious, expensive, or ready to claim.

\textbf{Trial-to-behavior conversion} is the agent-side loop. A signal at iteration $t$ must alter an action at iteration $t+k$: which direction to try, which evidence to distrust, which validation to run earlier, how strongly to state a claim, when to stop a branch, how to allocate GPU budget, or when to delay writing. The conversion must be more than a verbal lesson. It must appear in a later plan, experiment, review, schedule, or claim boundary. In our audit unit, a conversion links three artifacts: a trial signal, a later behavior change, and a trace path connecting them through a decision, reflection, task plan, review, or evolution record. Figure~\ref{fig:conversionevent} shows this unit.

\textbf{Evidence maturity} is the boundary that prevents trial-and-error from collapsing into paper generation. Execution completion, pilot signal, analysis-ready evidence, paper-ready evidence, and audited claim are different states. Moving between them requires validation, scope control, and artifact links. A completed run can still support only a weak signal. A negative result can increase maturity by ruling out a false story. A strong harness therefore treats claim advancement as a controlled transition, not as a default consequence of writing.

\begin{figure}[t]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=0.95\linewidth,height=0.22\textheight,keepaspectratio]{fig3_auditable_conversion_event.png}
  \caption{An auditable conversion event links a trial signal, a trace path, and a later behavior change. This figure defines the unit used in the process-evidence audit.}
  \label{fig:conversionevent}
\end{figure}

\textbf{Trial-to-harness-behavior conversion} is the harness-side loop. Some signals are not only about the research question; they are about the environment that produced the research. Repeated missing artifacts, incomplete telemetry, stale outputs, synchronization errors, or gates that admit weak evidence are evidence that the harness itself should change. The next trial should be proposed, executed, checked, remembered, and written under better constraints.

Together these loops define \emph{agent-harness co-evolution}. The research loop lets the agent accumulate domain judgment from trials. The harness loop improves the environment in which later trials happen. Autonomous research should not merely search within a fixed scaffold. It should use its own failures to strengthen the harness that shapes the next search.

These definitions imply observable commitments. Evaluation should ask whether trial history changed future behavior, whether claims moved through explicit maturity states, whether memories were routed to the roles that needed them, whether artifacts made the update auditable, and whether repeated process failures changed the harness itself. Figure~\ref{fig:evaluation} illustrates the boundary between task completion and claim maturity.

\begin{figure}[t]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=\linewidth,height=0.24\textheight,keepaspectratio]{fig6_evaluation_and_boundary.png}
  \caption{Evaluation should distinguish task completion from claim maturity. A claim-evidence gate can allow, downgrade, or block claims based on artifacts, validation checks, negative evidence, and reviewer objections.}
  \label{fig:evaluation}
\end{figure}

