\section{\sibyl{}: how the framework is implemented}
\label{sec:sibyl}

\sibyl{} instantiates the framework above as a file-backed, multi-stage autonomous research harness. The purpose is to make experience accumulation observable: a state machine records which research stage is active, which decision allows the next transition, which trial signals changed future research behavior, and which recurring process failures changed the harness itself.

The implementation is organized around seven surfaces. \textbf{Trial orchestration} gives each trial a contract: question, expected outputs, dependencies, and stop conditions; in \texttt{dynamic-wd}, this contract expands into a 14-task refinement plan after UDWDC instability and budget confounds. \textbf{Evidence boundary} keeps execution state separate from claim maturity through gates and scoped advancement; in \texttt{augmentation-order}, pilot completion and a \texttt{GO} signal still leave full-scale claims blocked. \textbf{Research memory} stores obligations rather than transcripts, routing lessons to the roles that must act on them; the central evolution ledger contains 173 outcome records and a digest of 416 recurring issue patterns. \textbf{Perspective separation} makes objections actionable by turning critique into tasks, claim changes, or stopped branches; in \texttt{sae-absorption-kimi}, supervisor and critic scores overrule an 8/10 writing score when duplicated replicates and feature-count mismatches break the evidence base. \textbf{Resource efficiency} makes scheduling and stopping responsive to evidence quality; in \texttt{dlm-acceleration}, low-value pilots and acceleration overhead produce sanity-check-first planning rather than more expensive blind runs. \textbf{Artifact trace and claim-evidence graphs} make learning externally inspectable. \textbf{Harness self-evolution} turns recurring process failures into routed lessons, prompt overlays, gates, and repair surfaces.

These surfaces are implemented across six internal planes: control, evidence, memory, role, compute, and evolution. The control plane contains explicit decision and quality gates. The evidence plane stores workspace artifacts, event logs, reviews, and claim traces. The memory plane turns reflection into issue categories and prompt overlays. The role plane separates innovators, skeptics, methodologists, critics, supervisors, and writers. The compute plane treats experiments as asynchronous workloads with GPU scheduling, dependencies, leases, monitoring, and recovery. The evolution plane accumulates cross-project lessons, routes issues to affected roles or system components, and creates repair tasks when the harness itself must change.

Table~\ref{tab:sibylmapping} maps each observable commitment from Table~\ref{tab:evaluation} to the \sibyl{} mechanism that makes it inspectable.

\begin{table}[t]
  \centering
  \small
  \setlength{\tabcolsep}{3pt}
  \caption{\sibyl{} implementation surfaces and the behavior updates they make observable.}
  \label{tab:sibylmapping}
  \begin{tabularx}{\linewidth}{p{0.23\linewidth}p{0.25\linewidth}Y}
    \toprule
    Framework role & \sibyl{} mechanism & Observable update \\
    \midrule
    Trial-to-behavior conversion & State machine and task plans & Earlier evidence changes the next plan, dependency, pilot/full transition, or branch priority. \\
    Evidence maturity control & Decision gates and validation requirements & Weak evidence triggers \texttt{REFINE}, pivot, claim downgrade, or writing restriction. \\
    Routed research memory & Reflection, evolution, and prompt overlays & Recurring issues become lessons for planners, experimenters, critics, supervisors, or writers. \\
    Actionable critique & Role-separated agents and debates & Objections become validation tasks, plan mutations, or scoped claims rather than free-form disagreement. \\
    Resource-aware trial policy & GPU scheduler and recovery & Failed or wasteful trials change sanity-check policy, allocation, monitoring, or recovery behavior. \\
    Auditable experience & Workspace artifacts and event logs & Claims and updates trace back to plans, logs, results, reviews, and negative evidence. \\
    Trial-to-harness-behavior conversion & Evolution records, self-heal, and sentinels & Recurring process failures become prompt overlays, validation gates, telemetry requirements, protected constraints, or repair tasks. \\
    \bottomrule
  \end{tabularx}
\end{table}

In \sibyl{}, writing and research roles do not share the same permissions, and these permissions are scientific integrity mechanisms rather than only engineering choices. A writer can synthesize validated claims but cannot silently upgrade a pilot result. A supervisor can allow advancement, but only with scoped risks. A critic can object, but the objection must become a task or boundary condition. A scheduler can run long experiments, but should first exploit cheap checks when the expected evidence value is low.

The implementation runs as two coupled loops. The research loop coordinates a single project: debate an idea, plan trials, run experiments, analyze evidence, write scoped claims, review, reflect, and pass a quality gate. The harness loop converts recurring failures into lessons, prompt overlays, artifact checks, telemetry requirements, and repair tasks that later projects inherit. Together with the role-based permissions above, these loops make \sibyl{} auditable at the point where experience should matter. A failed trial can be traced to a later plan mutation, a reviewer objection to a validation task, and a repeated infrastructure failure to a new gate or repair request.

\section{Process evidence from \sibyl{} workspaces and evolution records}
\label{sec:process-evidence}

We audit \sibyl{} workspaces and system-evolution records at the level required by the framework: a trial signal, a later change in research behavior or harness behavior, and the route that connects the signal to the change. The strongest evidence is temporal. A project first exposes a concrete failure or surprising result; the harness then records a gate, critique, reflection, task plan, or evolution entry; a later iteration changes experiments, claims, schedules, validation order, or harness checks. Audit traces use the path convention \texttt{<workspace>/iter\_NNN/<role>/<artifact>}.

The workspace set combines full research projects, ablation-style diagnostic projects, and evolution records. Full workspaces expose whether weak, negative, or surprising trial signals change plans, validation order, claim scope, and resource policy. Ablation workspaces remove or weaken debate, negative memory, validation, revision, or routed design lessons, exposing what happens when a route is missing. Evolution records capture the harness-side loop: recurring artifact, telemetry, synchronization, and writing failures are normalized into issue categories, affected roles, suggestions, repair tasks, and prompt or gate updates. Figure~\ref{fig:workspace-cases} summarizes the workspace evidence map and one gate-to-action flow; Appendix~\ref{sec:extended-cases} preserves detailed timelines.

