  \centering
  \begin{subfigure}[t]{0.49\linewidth}
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=\linewidth,height=0.22\textheight,keepaspectratio]{fig4_workspace_process_evidence.png}
    \caption{Cross-workspace evidence map.}
    \label{fig:workspace}
  \end{subfigure}
  \hfill
  \begin{subfigure}[t]{0.49\linewidth}
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=\linewidth,height=0.22\textheight,keepaspectratio]{fig5_dynamic_wd_case_flow.png}
    \caption{Dynamic-WD gate-to-action flow.}
    \label{fig:dynamicwd}
  \end{subfigure}
  \caption{Workspace and system evidence audit trial-to-behavior conversion and trial-to-harness-behavior conversion. The map summarizes conversion traces and ablation contrasts; the case flow shows one \texttt{REFINE}-to-action path.}
  \label{fig:workspace-cases}
\end{figure}

\paragraph{Trial signals changed research behavior.} The clearest traces are multi-iteration sequences where a bad or surprising signal forces a different future action.

In \texttt{dynamic-wd}, iteration 13 identified factual paper errors, budget-equivalence concerns, corrupted controls, hidden negative BEM results, and the need for 90-epoch ImageNet validation. The next decision did not smooth these into prose. Iteration 14 inserted UDWDC-v2 with floor clipping, EMA smoothing, and epoch budget assertions; all 9 of 9 stability tests passed. The same decision file records that the Kp-only variant's weight-decay budget changed from 0.0 in v1 to 90.61 in v2, ImageNet CSI reached 0.987, H6 was no longer supported, and the ImageNet budget confound remained a major risk. The behavior update was not a single sentence of reflection: it changed the algorithm, the task plan, the validation order, and the claim boundary before issuing \texttt{ADVANCE}.

In \texttt{dlm-acceleration}, iteration 1 repaired seven concrete paper and analysis errors: fabricated Wilcoxon p-values, a tau$=0.0$ paradox, wrong failure-atlas numbers, inconsistent QAS formulas, a six-pair scope claim that only had three pairs, novelty overclaiming, and an inconsistent M3 speedup report. The same reflection then found a new quantitative error: the draft repeatedly claimed $\alpha=0.52$, while the measured accept rate was 0.881. Iteration 2 reframed the paper around interference rather than multiplicative speedup. Its result-debate verdict reports 15 experiment groups, M1 as a functional no-op at 1.16$\times$, destructive M1+M3 interference with ortho 0.41--0.52, M3+IGSD partial interference with ortho 0.61--0.84, and an AR comparison where Qwen2.5-7B reached 96\% GSM8K at 70.9--471.1 TPS. The update path is concrete: unsupported statistics and broken metrics changed the paper's thesis, added null ablations and full-scale replication prerequisites, and forced per-token speed to be separated from output-length effects.

In \texttt{sae-absorption}, iteration 10 is especially revealing because it contains both scientific progress and harness pressure. The iteration completed targeted full-mode analyses and produced a strong probe-degradation result ($R^2=0.777$, $\rho=-1.0$, $p=0.009$), but the project score regressed from 7.0 to 6.5 because new data-integrity errors entered the paper: confidence-interval inversion, three incompatible first-letter absorption rates, stale headline ratios, and unverified cross-domain patching. The reflection notes that \texttt{validate\_integration.py} had been recommended for ten consecutive iterations and still did not exist. Iteration 11 then turned the failure into a gate: \texttt{validate\_integration.py} was implemented, 51 of 53 checks passed, confidence-interval inversions were fixed, per-token aggregation became canonical, the stale 4.1$\times$ headline was reduced to 2.7$\times$, probe degradation became the first contribution, and a 20-entity spot check confirmed the corrected city-continent patching signal (62.7\% mean recovery vs. 61.9\% expected, $d=2.04$, $p<0.001$). This is exactly the kind of signal a paper generator would hide and a harness must surface: experiments improved, but the evidence-to-writing path had to be repaired before the paper could advance.

In \texttt{sae-absorption-kimi}, the harness caught an even sharper failure: writing quality improved while the experimental foundation collapsed. Iteration 8 received a writing score of 8/10, but the supervisor score fell to 4.5/10 and the critic score to 5/10 after verification found that 4 of 5 Matryoshka replicates were byte-identical to MultiScale across nine metrics, the implementation used \texttt{NUM\_FEATURES=1024} while the paper claimed 16,384 features, the L0-matched ablation was missing, all trained variants had negative explained variance, TopK had 81.6\% dead latents, and the canonical summary contained only 3 of 7 variants. The future behavior changed accordingly: duplicate detection, feature-count verification, L0 controls, convergence diagnostics, and a single source-of-truth analysis pipeline became prerequisites before narrative generation.

\paragraph{Diagnostic workspaces expose missing update paths.} The diagnostic workspaces stress specific routes from trial signal to later behavior. They are artifact-rich stress tests for the update paths themselves. When a route is absent, weak, or misaligned, the expected failure becomes visible: \texttt{ablation-no-debate} reaches a pilot \texttt{GO} while one absorption metric separates trained and random SAEs and another saturates at 1.00 for both; \texttt{ablation-mem-negative} reaches a quality-gate hard block when iteration 5 has no review score; \texttt{ablation-no-revision} records long stagnation and recurring issues that were not escalated into enforced action. Table~\ref{tab:ablations} records the diagnostic condition, the missing conversion, and the observed failure trace.

\paragraph{Evolution records show harness self-evolution.} The \texttt{.sibyl/evolution} records implement the harness-side loop. They normalize reflection outputs into issue categories, severities, affected agents, suggestions, statuses, and success patterns. The central ledger contains 173 outcome records; its digest contains 416 recurring issue patterns, with the largest mass in experiment, writing, and analysis issues. Routing is explicit: experiment issues are assigned to experimenter/server-experimenter/planner roles, analysis issues to supervisor/critic/skeptic/reflection, and writing issues to section-writer/editor/codex-writer roles. The prompt loader then injects selected lessons as role-specific overlays. Runtime boundaries also appear in artifacts: \texttt{ablation-mem-negative} hard-blocks iteration 5 for a missing review score and rolls back to review. This is trial-to-harness-behavior conversion in its strongest observable form: repeated failures are compressed into routed memory, role prompts, quality gates, and repair surfaces that shape the next research loop.

