The audit reads this table in three ways. First, every primary workspace has at least one file-backed iteration with role artifacts, so \texttt{REFINE}, \texttt{GO}, \texttt{NO\_GO}, \texttt{PIVOT}, and \texttt{ADVANCE} markers are observable rather than inferred. Second, dense \texttt{REFINE}/\texttt{NO\_GO} surfaces identify where timeline audit should look for claim repair, validation, and scope control before advancement. The clearest case is \texttt{dlm-acceleration}: 166 \texttt{REFINE} marker occurrences, 43 \texttt{NO\_GO} markers, and only 6 \texttt{ADVANCE} markers match the detailed trace in which unsupported statistics, baseline confusion, and metric failures force a new interference taxonomy. Third, the diagnostic rows show that execution can proceed while a route stays weak: \texttt{ablation-no-revision} has five failed tasks and zero \texttt{REFINE} markers, while \texttt{ablation-mem-negative} reaches an explicit quality-gate rollback.

Two smaller workspaces serve as boundary checks. \texttt{augmentation-order} distinguishes workflow completion from claim maturity: visible task completion did not make the evidence ready for general claims. \texttt{lewm-generalization} shows that real autonomous research quickly becomes a scheduling and recovery problem, so resource policy is part of the research loop rather than background engineering.

\section{Evaluation protocols, governance, and alternative views}

The commitments in Table~\ref{tab:evaluation} define what should be measured. Practical evaluation should therefore stress update paths rather than only final artifacts. A retrospective audit asks whether a completed workspace exposes trial signals, behavior updates, maturity changes, and evidence paths. A fixed-budget comparison gives multiple harnesses the same research question and measures which system produces better-scoped claims, stronger traces, fewer repeated failures, and lower human audit burden. Cross-project memory and harness-evolution tests ask whether failures in one project change the behavior or infrastructure of later projects. Appendix~\ref{sec:appendix-eval-protocols} gives a more detailed protocol list.

The present evidence is concentrated in one author-built harness and in computational AI/ML research workspaces. The diagnostic ablations are process diagnostics rather than repeated statistical experiments, and transfer to wet-lab, theory-heavy, or non-AI domains remains future work.

The strongest protocol is an injected-failure stress test because it is controlled and directly tied to scientific integrity. The harness can be probed with duplicate result files, confidence-interval inversion, stale tables, feature-count mismatches between a manifest and run output, missing seeds, or unsupported significance claims. A passing system blocks or downgrades narrative generation, routes the issue to the role responsible for the affected artifact, and preserves the negative evidence for future memory. The current workspace evidence already contains naturally occurring versions of these failures, such as duplicate data, confidence-interval inversion, stale tables, missing figures, and unsupported statistics. An injected test turns those naturally occurring failures into a controlled benchmark for evidential boundary defense.

Alternative views sharpen the claim because the workspaces contain direct counterexamples.
\begin{itemize}
  \item \emph{Paper generation is already a sufficient benchmark, because a good paper implicitly requires good evidence.} \texttt{sae-absorption-kimi} is the counterexample: paper-facing quality reached 8/10 while duplicated replicates, a feature-count mismatch, missing L0 control, negative explained variance, and dead latents invalidated the evidence base.
  \item \emph{Metric-driven loops or long context are enough.} \texttt{dlm-acceleration} is the counterexample: fabricated p-values, alpha 0.52 versus measured accept rate 0.881, M1 as a 1.16$\times$ no-op, and destructive composition interference required objective critique and new full-scale gates, not more optimization against the same story.
  \item \emph{Human oversight removes the need for autonomous memory.} Human responsibility remains central, but the system must expose a trace that lets humans inspect claims without reconstructing every trial from scratch. The 411 tracked tasks and evolution records are what make oversight scalable.
  \item \emph{Harness self-evolution is only engineering hygiene.} The quality-gate hard block in \texttt{ablation-mem-negative}, routed evolution lessons, and role-specific prompt overlays show the opposite: the engineering substrate determines what evidence the agent can collect, trust, remember, and learn from.
\end{itemize}

\begin{table}[t]
  \centering
  \small
  \setlength{\tabcolsep}{3pt}
  \caption{Governance risks: each row pairs a failure mode with the harness mechanism that enables it and the mitigation that constrains it.}
  \label{tab:governance}
  \begin{tabularx}{\linewidth}{p{0.27\linewidth}p{0.32\linewidth}Y}
    \toprule
    Risk & Mechanism that enables it & Mitigation \\
    \midrule
    Scientific spam & Treating paper completion as success & Claim-evidence gates and validation-first writing \\
    Rhetorical overclaiming & Writer holding full claim authority & Maturity-labeled claim registry consumed by writers \\
    Metric gaming on harness scores & Single maturity score becoming a proxy & Multi-dimensional labels and hidden injected failures \\
    Negative memory suppressing exploration & Lessons over-generalized & Time decay, source links, and re-opening criteria \\
    Self-evolution drift & Prompt overlays or gates optimizing fluency & Periodic memory audits against an integrity baseline \\
    Unsafe harness self-modification & Repair tasks weakening protected constraints & Human-reviewed protected files, regression tests, and rollback logs \\
    \bottomrule
  \end{tabularx}
\end{table}

Governance follows from the same logic. Table~\ref{tab:governance} lists risks and mitigations. Our stance is constrained autonomy: agents can explore, fail, and repair inside a system that preserves evidence boundaries and leaves a human-auditable trace. The harness can improve itself only through versioned changes, protected constraints, tests, and human review for safety-relevant surfaces. In low-risk computational domains, this permits substantial autonomous iteration. In high-risk domains, the same harness logic should become stricter, with human approval gates before real-world actions and domain-specific safety constraints before trials begin. Appendix~\ref{sec:appendix-governance-details} records additional governance details.

\section{Conclusion}

Autonomous research should not be judged mainly by whether a system can generate a complete paper. A paper is an expression of an evidence state. The harder capability is whether a system can accumulate research experience: conduct controlled trials, preserve what went right and wrong, revise its future behavior, improve the harness that hosts it, and make the whole process auditable.

We argued that research judgment can be operationalized as accumulated trial experience whose effects appear as trial-to-behavior conversion. We proposed Scientific Trial-and-Error Harnesses as the design target for autonomous research. We described \sibyl{} as one concrete implementation, with decision gates, artifact traces, role-separated agents, routed memory, GPU-aware experiment control, and system-evolution records. The central claim is that the next generation of autonomous research systems should compete on how safely, efficiently, and honestly they convert trial history into future research behavior and future harness behavior.

