\section{Implementation details}

This appendix expands the implementation sketch from the main text. It is written as system evidence for the harness claim, not as a full software manual. The relevant unit is the research behavior update or harness behavior update that the mechanism makes possible.

\subsection{Harness component mapping}

\begin{table}[ht]
  \centering
  \small
  \setlength{\tabcolsep}{3pt}
  \caption{Detailed mapping from harness functions to \sibyl{} implementation surfaces.}
  \label{tab:appendixmapping}
  \begin{tabularx}{\linewidth}{p{0.22\linewidth}p{0.35\linewidth}Y}
    \toprule
	    Harness component & Implementation surface & Why it matters for experience conversion \\
    \midrule
    Trial orchestration & Explicit state machine, idea debate, planning, pilot/full experiment stages, parallel task dispatch. & Trials become planned, bounded events rather than free-form tool calls. \\
    Evidence boundary & Idea and experiment decisions, quality gates, validation requirements, self-heal substrate, artifact checks. & Weak or corrupted evidence can block writing, force \texttt{REFINE}, or cause a pivot. \\
    Research memory & Reflection postprocess, evolution issue categories, lesson overlays, prompt injection. & Failures can reappear as role-specific checks in later iterations or projects. \\
    Perspective separation & Role-separated ideation, critique, methodology, supervision, writing, and review. & Disagreement can be converted into a task, claim downgrade, or validation boundary. \\
    Resource efficiency & GPU scheduler, dependency graph, dynamic dispatch, monitoring, recovery, and sanity-check lessons. & Trial cost affects whether an autonomous system can accumulate useful experience. \\
    Artifact trace & Workspace status, event logs, checkpoints, experiment state, review artifacts, writing artifacts, and LaTeX outputs. & Human authors can audit whether behavior really changed and why. \\
    Harness self-evolution & Evolution digests, global lessons, affected-agent routing, self-heal tasks, sentinel checks, and protected constraints. & Process failures become harness changes instead of recurring as project-local mistakes. \\
    \bottomrule
  \end{tabularx}
\end{table}

\subsection{State machine and typed actions}

\sibyl{} uses an explicit multi-stage artifact-backed state machine. The current stage list includes initialization, literature search, idea debate, planning, pilot experiments, idea validation, experiment cycles, result debate, experiment decisions, outline writing, section writing, integration, final writing review, LaTeX generation, review, reflection, quality gate, and completion. We avoid using a brittle stage count in the main text because the scientific claim is not the number of stages; it is that stage transitions are file-backed and gate-controlled.

The orchestrator also returns typed actions rather than only natural-language instructions. Examples include single-skill calls, parallel skill calls, team actions, parallel agents, shell execution, GPU polling, experiment waiting, completion, and stopped states. This matters because a typed action can be inspected, retried, or blocked. A free-form instruction is harder to audit and harder to connect to later behavior.

\subsection{GPU scheduler and recovery}

The compute plane treats experiments as asynchronous workloads. A task plan is validated, converted into dependency layers, assigned resource needs, and dispatched under GPU leases. The scheduler polls device availability, tracks running tasks, records progress files, and supports recovery when an experiment is interrupted. This makes trials cheaper to monitor and easier to resume, which affects how quickly evidence can mature.

\begin{table}[ht]
  \centering
  \small
  \setlength{\tabcolsep}{3pt}
  \caption{Compute-plane artifacts and their scientific role.}
  \label{tab:computeplane}
  \begin{tabularx}{\linewidth}{p{0.23\linewidth}p{0.34\linewidth}Y}
    \toprule
    Artifact or mechanism & Function & Harness interpretation \\
    \midrule
    Task plan & Declares tasks, dependencies, outputs, and resource needs. & Converts research intent into bounded trials with artifact contracts. \\
    Dependency layers & Order tasks by prerequisites and critical path. & Prevents invalid comparisons caused by missing prerequisites. \\
    GPU leases and polling & Coordinate scarce accelerator resources. & Makes efficiency a scientific constraint, not only an engineering concern. \\
    Progress and experiment state files & Record running, completed, failed, or recoverable work. & Distinguish execution state from claim maturity. \\
    Recovery logic & Resumes or repairs interrupted workloads when possible. & Reduces repeated work and makes long trials auditable. \\
    \bottomrule
  \end{tabularx}
\end{table}

\subsection{Reflection and evolution memory}

The memory layer starts from reflection artifacts, but it should not end there. Reflection outputs are normalized into issue categories such as system, experiment, writing, analysis, planning, pipeline, ideation, and efficiency. The evolution layer maintains digests and lessons, computes relevance, and injects selected lessons into later prompts. This is the mechanism behind the paper's distinction between long context and research memory. Long context can expose past text; routed memory can change which checks a role performs.

Memory effectiveness is measured by behavior, not volume. A lesson informs the system when it reduces repeated failures, changes a plan, adds a validation step, changes a claim boundary, or repairs the harness path that allowed the failure. The memory layer therefore stores source links, uncertainty, decay, and re-opening criteria alongside the lesson text.

\subsection{Decision gates, self-heal, and writing boundaries}

The current system exposes idea validation, experiment decisions, quality gates, review stages, and a structured self-heal substrate. The self-heal layer includes error collection, routing, protected-file constraints, deterministic fixers for recurring failure classes, and repair-task generation. These mechanisms improve workflow reliability and create places where failures become tasks before they recur in the next research loop.

The natural boundary surface is a validated claim registry. Writing agents consume claims with maturity labels, artifact links, and validation status. Pilot signals remain usable as pilot signals. A paper is generated from the claim registry, not from whatever narrative is most fluent after the latest experiment.

